Can't afford an eletric car right now (I don't live in the US, electric cars here comes only at luxury import prices) and will drive my '97 Ford Fiesta 'till it becomes garbage, but some questions comes to mind which weren't exposed in the video:

1. Total pollution sum. I know that electric cars don't exhaust CO and other pollutants, but how does it stack up to Lithium Ion batteries - because those are pollutants too. They not only have toxic components in them, but there's a cycle of production and replacement to consider. Of course the entire infrastructure involved in extration, transportation and whatnot for gas also have separate impacts to make for a total comparison, but it'd be interesting to see a study on that (there probably already is, but I mean on the video comparison);

2. Lithium Ion safety concerns. This is a problem in both cases of course... petrol chambers and other energy sources like biogas can be pretty explosive and flammable too. But Lithion Ion is not only flammable, we also have some very graphic examples of thermal runaway. When you are driving around in a car in which entire bottom is basically made of a chain of batteries with potential for thermal runaway, the results of a crash or even a single battery failure can become extremely dramatic. I understand several extra steps were taken to make things more secure for cars like the Tesla models, but we'll have to see how things go in real life scenarios overtime;

Other than that, agreed that the overall engineering of it is simplified by several degrees. The jury is still out for me though. I totally understand that battery technology is expected to improve in several ways over the years, but I have no intention of spending a whole ton of money right now if a safer and less polluting battery tech is right around the corner. I understand that the industry needs funding to move forwards, but you know... I have no money to burn.

